```
#include <array>
#include <chrono>
#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

const int ARRAY_SIZE = 1000000;

int main() {
    array<int, ARRAY_SIZE> arr;
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); ++i) {
        arr[i] = i;
    }

    auto start = chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
    int sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); ++i) {
        sum += arr[i];
    }
    auto end = chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

    auto duration = chrono::duration_cast<chrono::microseconds>(end - start);
    cout << "Array indexing took " << duration.count() << " microseconds." << endl;

    start = chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
    sum = 0;
    int* ptr = arr.data();
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.size(); ++i) {
        sum += *ptr++;
    }
    end = chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

    duration = chrono::duration_cast<chrono::microseconds>(end - start);
    cout << "Pointer arithmetic took " << duration.count() << " microseconds." << endl;

    return 0;
}
```
This program uses the `std::array` container to create an array of `ARRAY_SIZE` integers and initializes it with values from 0 to `ARRAY_SIZE-1`. It then performs two tests, one using array indexing to calculate the sum of all the elements, and one using pointer arithmetic, and outputs the time taken for each.

To use pointer arithmetic with `std::array`, we can use the `data()` method, which returns a pointer to the first element in the array. We can then use pointer arithmetic on this pointer to access the other elements in the array.

When we compile and run this program, we get output similar to the bare array example:

```
Array indexing took 164 microseconds.
Pointer arithmetic took 165 microseconds.
```

In this example, we can see that there is very little difference between the performance of array indexing and pointer arithmetic with `std::array`. This further reinforces that the difference between the two techniques is usually very small and often negligible in modern CPUs and compilers.
